content.description: Sit start with hands matched on the shelf. From there, place a heel, move up through a pair of jugs, then pull to a right hand edge, bump the left hand up to the far arete, commit to the slab, and top it out.
content.protection: A pad or two. The landing is good, but there is a rock in the left part of the fall zone.
content.location: It climbs the south facing overhang on Fenceline.

content.description: Stand start with opposing sidepulls. From there, reach a right hand edge, gain a diagonal jug rail with the left hand, match, commit to the final slab, and mantel on top.
content.protection: A pad will work. The landing is perfect.
content.location: It climbs the north face of Fenceline.

content.description:
Brown Bear Benching climbs a slightly overhung lowball made of great rock via compression movement.

Sit start with a left hand edge and a right hand triangle-pinch. From there, pull up to a left hand edge, follow with right hand to a nothing-sidepull-divot, bump the left hand up to a sidepull, then reach a right hand jug up top, match hands, throw a high right foot, and press out the mantle for the finish.
content.protection: Two pads worked well. The immediate landing is flat, but there are a pair of rocks behind the problem.
content.location: It climbs the east face of Fenceline.
